******
[5]
Date: Mon 9 Jan 2023
Source: Nation [edited]
https://www.nation.com.pk/09-Jan-2023/nih-team-arrives-in-ry-khan-to-collect-samples-for-epidemiological-investigation


Under the direction of the National Command and Operations Centre (NCOC), a team comprising three members from the National Institute of Health (NIH) arrived in Rahim Yar Khan (RYK) on Sunday [8 Jan 2023] for epidemiological investigation and sampling of viral and bacterial diseases from the community of affected family in Basti Behram Laghari said District Health Officer Dr Liaqat Ali Chohan on Sunday.

The team members also took samples from animals to rule out any zoonotic disease. The team also examined the houses, inquired the relatives of the deceased about their use of food, and gathered details about cattle and pets. Keeping in view the situation of a suspected outbreak of meningitis-like illness in Rukanpur area of district Rahim Yar Khan, under the directions of NCOC, NIH deputed a multi-disciplinary team to investigate this outbreak, collect necessary information from patients, contacts, and community and collect necessary samples in order to support the disease confirmation. Chief Executive Officer of District Health Authority Dr Hassan Khan said that no further affected person was reported with mysterious disease symptoms on Sunday [8 Jan 2023]. He said that DHA requested the country's national level health forum NIH to investigate the cause of death of unknown diseases.

[Byline: Ihsan Ul Haq]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[An outbreak of a fatal undiagnosed disease is occurring in Basti Behram Laghari village of Rahim Yar District, Pakistan. Rahim Yar Khan (pop., almost 800 000 residents in 2017) is the capital city of Rahim Yar Khan District in Punjab Province, Pakistan (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahim_Yar_Khan). Sheikh Zaid Medical College, where affected patients are hospitalized, is in the city of Rahim Yar Khan (https://szmc.edu.pk). A map showing the location of Rahim Yar Khan can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Rahim+Yar+Khan,+Punjab,+Pakistan.

The illness has killed 12 people so far and hospitalized another 11. The dead are said to be mainly children and those hospitalized vary from 1.5 to 60 years of age. The several news reports above have characterized the illness as either meningitis or meningoencephalitis, but details of its clinical presentation, results of laboratory tests done, or its epidemiology are not given.

More information from knowledgeable sources would be appreciated. - Mod.ML]
